Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament, in the context of an amendment to criminal law, refused the draft annulment of the paragraph on the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs refused at second reading the proposed amendment to reduce penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for reaching a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court must rule on the appeal of the convicted person in December.
Tymosenko qualifies the regime's judgment as political revenge and has provoked a process of suspicions of bias of the court also in the west.
The plan to annul paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve.
