IBM Story: From the slices of cheese to the thefts in the cosmos.
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it originally had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 80's of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the former "pointers", the clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 presided over the supervisory board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the firm's founder - it is on Watson's ideas that the identity and culture of society have been based until now.
Watson ran the firm until 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machinery for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In the first four years that Watson led, revenue increased to US$9 million and began the firm’s expansion in all parts of the world.
Watson was for the firm so irreplaceable that after 40 years of management it was his son who occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM people and computers helped NASA guide flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the Moon.
Meanwhile in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 came to market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought Consulting’s Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has succeeded at IBM over the past three years – is the Smarter Planet concept “a smarter planet.”
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited such as transport and city management.
Regarding the field of IBM commerce, a short time ago, an "Smarter Commerce" platform has developed a platform that helps salespeople to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history also in our territory.
She established her branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center of Brno.
The Central for Central and Eastern Europe is headquartered in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team responsible for speech recognition.
