How have travel prices changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have an inclination for the west and travels to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually for example in Poland or the Soviet Union he needed a letter of invitation otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency agreement that was the condition for traveling west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable, however, and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and chalets that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The Czechs’ travels have since seen a great revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at the maximum, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million days of vacation in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 90's of the last century in the neighboring countries of the west caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially in Austria to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least a moment.
For example in Paris, travel organizations put Czechs to sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czechs trip was at that time to take with you your own canned food, sausage, etc... to save money.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech krona which allowed our tourists finally after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage have increased, which has caused another important time around 1997.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have begun since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter connections that through contracts have tremendously reduced costs compared to what was before.
By the end of the 90's of the last century, the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world apart from the US, which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when was prepared the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to the distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
It is more than 100000 Czechs who visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully side in the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15 000 kronor per person on holidays abroad including the ancillary charges. Crowns per person.
