21st House in Vienna
The Pavilion that moved
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups, downs and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and serves as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about a modern post-war architecture, for its clear forms, glass sheds, bright and bold looks and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the Universal Exhibition in Brussels in 1958 is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its lightweight and suspended steel and glass construction.
Construction is considered to this day as an important step in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the following Austrian World's Fair.
With its legendary four-cylinder BMW home and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it eventually became internationally famous in 1973.
His project of pavilion as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the World's Fair in the Swiss Garden at the South Vienna Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang artworks, so not a good environment.
However it has been used for so long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and has become increasingly dilapidated.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name of "House of the 21st century" and will in the future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the Belvédère museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a stroke of luck from any point of view.
The new start was carried out by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director in 2007 of the Austrian gallery Belvédère.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as a figure skater, subsequently at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she carried out the work of transformation among politicians and the protection of monuments, she obtained public and private sponsorship funds.
Except for contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited, a café and a bookstore are there, and an office must be built there.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had transformed and expanded with sensitivity the secession of Joseph Olbracht and he had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "virtually every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he was aware of the problems of the building, which lost generosity and lightness following his trip to Vienna and his change of use.
During the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "a chasm in energy", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, glass-fibre-reinforced insulating glass was laid and the roof replaced by a particular safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges have been reinforced or replaced, and the coatings filled with asbestos have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a panel of light sifted between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it is almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors remained, the house is painted in a shade of protection against rust of red-brown color.
And the movie theater is even exactly the same as what it once was.
And all this under the close supervision of the competent authorities for the monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and cheap were to be found, and that also please the protection office monuments," says Krischanitz and he draws attention to a raw soil in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
It would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz said recently, a typical story of "Drop-in-the-City".
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a stroke of chance of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands precisely the "neighborhood of the central station" all newly planned, with offices and apartments.
And another stroke of luck may happen: the House of the 21st century could benefit from the reinforcement of another construction Krischanitz, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the temporary art center Berlin, and as it says, it is already negotiating with the city in order to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
