Peter Englund’s new book offers depth and generosity. Titled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War", it begins with a long list of characters that shakes your heart.
A tip to start with: tear this page thoroughly and make it your bookmark.
You will get to know these people in detail. In this novelistic account of Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mists of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
He wrote here an extraordinary book that he accurately describes as "a work of anti-history."
It has some known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and material.
It’s not so much a book about what happened, he explains, that a “book describing what it could look like.” We find the "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and grief" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 men and women more or less ordinary, on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, paramedics and salespeople.
Some will become heroes.
Other prisoners of war. Some will lose limbs, go crazy or lose their lives.
Their lives waver here like the candles of a church: while some are dying out, new ones are rekindled.
Peter Englund's book departs from traditional history books.
It brings a denial to the idea that the First World War is only summarized by the terrible war of the trenches on the Western front.
"Beauty and grief" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; one passes Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tse-tse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina who stinks the cordite.
When cannon shots ring in the distance, and you are a stay-at-home mother, do you stay or run away?
Who will come anyway?
Hardly anyone can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been fleshed out by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and Grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nanny in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor from the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly taken from memoirs, letters and other already published documents.
Versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved through the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most of them approach deprivation and the ability to get away with it.
Recounting the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz. "
