After the tragedy this summer, the researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy... Connect to Facebook.
“We realized that it wasn’t that hard to find them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a report recently published by DEMOS’ think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific precision — the way mercatics have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett’s team has discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right bands in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to respond to a survey. The questions asked were about their level of education, attitudes to violence and optimism about their own future.
By coming into contact with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to question 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
“It’s a new way of doing research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups are men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen.”
The study of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook has become the new must-have tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to "Like", wall publications and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three content per day, the "data supernova" generates a search explosion, increasing the number of search work whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn’t approach on the street.
“Before, when you were trying to investigate the people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You had to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you to enter,” Bartlett said.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information. "
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social issues.
According to a recent study by D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, the young students who spoke on Facebook about their drunken exploits were far more likely to be alcoholics than discrete students about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that student colleagues, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to eventually help a student whose status would speak too often about alcohol.
“You can’t treat a problem if you don’t diagnose it,” Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Health, Behaviour and Child Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would not be recognized in another case."
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The team at the site that handles the data studied statistics about the love situation and Valentine’s Day, the turnout in the 2010 midterm elections and a national happiness index (thanks to information only available – digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its data treasure available to other people for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of an investigation they haven’t even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect information other than through the Internet, it is quite another thing online.
“I don’t believe that a large number of users have already thought about the fact that a researcher can study their profile,” said Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, according to a 2006 study he conducted while observing his students’ Facebook walls.
"As far as they know, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user’s wall.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two totally different things,” Selwyn said.
That’s why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn thinks that a notebook and pen remain the best tools that can be used.
“Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people,” he said.
"Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect - and the social is not in front of a computer."
