7 lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview, at the cinema this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find most revealing in a recently found Steve Jobs interview that will be released this week in the opening part of a movie in major markets, is how much that creative mind understood the processes and workflows of products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as an organizational improver - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a "disease let them think that a great idea does 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds". This series traces the birth of the computer, and he sits for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it had been about 10 years since Steve Jobs had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aiming for a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in the transport.
It was only after the death of Steve Jobs that a full video was found in the director's garage.
This slightly rebounded video is the basis of the 68-minute film entitled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be broadcast at the cinema next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs seems surprisingly enthusiastic here to expose technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide a precise answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs' perfectionism resurfaces, when he seems eager to hear Cringely's questions, giving him elbows to speed up him and move on to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, we find a strangely prescient aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision for the future of IT.
It’s one thing to read the posthumous evaluations of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can be and should be.
He explains them and then the implementations in a row.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences from Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
"All these years, I've always asked, 'Why do you do things?' and the answers are constantly the same: 'oh, just because you have to do them.'"
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs goes on to elaborate on his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed about how costs were recorded - we often start with a "standard cost" evaluated at a nose view, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed the precise calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a trick on the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack the phone networks and phone for free in long distance.
The device has been the subject of many writings beforehand, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, passing a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We wrapped the ball of different things half a dozen times and you screamed in the public phone and it happened to you a minute later on the public phone next door,” Jobs laughs.
“We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we ourselves could create something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world. "
We didn’t know much about the two of us, but we knew how to invent a small thing that could control big things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs goes on to tell a wonderful trick that he and Wozniak have developed: he called the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night pretending to be Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love with technology (and canvassing Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searches for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gives him a phone call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“It had a remarkable influence on me. “It was the only company I’d seen at that age and it formed my definition of a company and how employees are treated.”
Steve Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the company’s research labs, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the “first ever-designed desktop.”
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode-ray tube. I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On the improvisation of innovation:
At several points in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a whim.
At the beginning of his career, as he settles down to sell a few circuit boards, a customer asks him to assemble a complete computer.
Working at only 30 days of credit, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big fights... I was shouted at pretending that it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and went to see a designer.”
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that was incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are running out of steam:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industrial leaders were going to be wrong and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [it’s these types of people] that end up running companies and product-specialized personnel are sidelined from decision-making.
The product genius that has led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who cannot imagine conceiving a good product in relation to a bad product - the required manual labor.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have made its current size ten times. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90's...
They snatched defeat from victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
"A huge part of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... As you develop this idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are some compromises to make... Some things you can’t do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by putting them together.
Finally, decisions are made for personal taste. It’s about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring those things to the product you’re creating.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We are always ashamed to steal some great ideas.
This is part of what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply proved to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
