How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines indicates how ubiquitous deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was taken by an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York City congressman and internet celebrity Anthony Weiner, passed for an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by compelling evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of campaign funding violations related to the coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of the people who lived the story will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton sparked while lying in his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating on the school and university tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers have given the test answers to students in order to be clear about their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should teach otherwise send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or identifying lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charads, where the goal is to exclaim: "I've had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research of such projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They do not stutter, blush or agitate always.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A qualified lie detector can uncover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial microexpressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation, or management.
Good liars are skilled at reading others well, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies “centered on them” while women say more lies “centered on others” – usually to protect someone’s feelings – that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "establishing benchmark data".
This helps to provide a benchmark for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, laughter, vocal quality.
You need to know if someone normally stirs their feet permanently so that you don’t make unfair charges when you see them moving their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of deceptive verbal and non-verbal behavior.
Think of these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the upper body when trying to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean towards a way out, change posture significantly, or present a “post-interview” relief – an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change in posture when all the difficult questions are gone.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is over just to seek to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson skidded using the past while pretending that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use a distant language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
