Climate adversity has slowed the economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment fell and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, self-called change, which has generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators.
Low temperatures in February, apart from causing trillion losses for the agricultural sector, limited the state economy's growth opportunities, caused a contraction in economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report of allocations by the Jellies from the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which a 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the rest of 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity generated, until November, a constant increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year there was an accelerated increase, because from January to March 55 thousand 053 sinaloens were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate has continued to increase to July to March 55 thousand 053 menA rate that represents more than 74 thousand unemployed Sinaloens, an increase from the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
“What we’re seeing is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, between which the loss of liquidity in the market due to a resource restriction by legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who make dollars in an illicit way is not easy for them to work to earn them, invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
“The number of people who abandon the state to go to work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because by entering they already have a lot of difficulties in finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which means that unemployment rises,” he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinalo labour market worsens by considering the high level of seriousness that predominates between working conditions, according to the INEGI, the 60.38 percent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and the lack of seriousness, another reason for the state's lag is low wages, the entity has the lower remunerations of the country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecasting.
The average monthly income of the Sinalian workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which is 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Aside from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the FDI of the State reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the State Government's Economic Development Secretariat accounts for a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, mainly registered by companies in the service sector.
The debt
Given the economic contraction scenario, the State Government requested in July the public congress the approval of a credit of 3 trillion pesos, intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the objective of reactivating the economy, the approval of the state congress was 2,600 trillion pesos and until November there was no profit of the debt.
Reactions
For representatives of the employer sector, the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of management capacity of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, herein included the State Government.
"The performance of the Sinaloa economy during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we had to align the effort of all and especially the already synchronized smooth running of this new government team, hope that next year is much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said that events like the frosts at the beginning of the year have retained the state economy and have restricted its yield and growth.
“The low economic flow is produced from several events, between which the frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close a lot below the expectations we had,” he said.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Patronal Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that it is desired to channel the state towards more productive activities of greater dynamism.
“In general terms we have observed that we have been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that we detonate the full potential of Sinaloa’s material and human resources,” he said.
Many to do
The President of the Coparex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to deliver good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in the way public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that we have worked a lot and the Government is aware that there is still much to be done," he said.
