The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have made against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been met.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree which details the actions to be taken to concretize the transition to terrestrial digital television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was rejected for not having reached the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to decide on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, developed by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as unconstitutional, because the regulation on radio and television is an assignment reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), contrary to the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favor of the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero himself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and admit the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all the actions planned by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of the Ministers also resolved to dismiss the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure measures through general standards to ensure that the public administration is prepared for it.
"I also only consider whether it does so would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate of the state leadership.
The substitution of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years and this translates into better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Adjourning change, he argued, would postpone the benefits of digitalization that involves a public interest decision that not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues."
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of an entire system establishes, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the state, encompasses a group of responsibilities that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State."
He recalled that a large number of countries from all over the world have already finished the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have the highly specialized technical bodies.
