Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with the President of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the verge of economic disaster and jeopardized the entire Eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in his majority by technocrats, even if it is not clear when the new executive will assume his position.
Monti said he would present the president with the outcome of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner for Journalists said.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
The "frame is now well traced," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normally, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration headed by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the trust in Italy that had been affected.
By highlighting the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets has placed the yield of Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level in which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti’s opportunities for success have been greatly stimulated by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, to which the crisis has forced to resign last Saturday.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts will have a good result,” Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the government of technocrat majority that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
Monti’s new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack by the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign benches has added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began its consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers’ groups and youth and women’s organizations on Monday.
He will finish his meeting tour Tuesday at night.
Monti was named Sunday by Napolitano, who has able to transition extremely quickly in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, it would be too much for the current financial defenses of Eurozone.
Monti said his Government should persist until future elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give it time to apply the reforms before advancing the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it must be formed only by specialists, a hint of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have pointed out that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties make it difficult to try to include political figures.
