The Communications and Transport Secretariat (SCT) has informed that the results highlighted on the accident in which Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and other seven people lost his life, indicate that the helicopter shocked directly against the ground in full structural integrity, without the pilot being able to try a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before the take-off of the aircraft, the pilot found that climate conditions were adequate to fly.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 persons, so it met the requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations done in the impact zone do not report the appearance of floor parts.
"In a search it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact presented itself structurally.
"The helicopter had been designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The ground had a swire of seven to 30 degrees inclination.
For the moment, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as quickly as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, General Manager of Aéroports and Auxiliary Services, assured that the moment of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential Maggiore State was operating in speed of cruising and this happened on an uphill soft ground.
“This information supports the hypothesis of normal functioning cruiser at the time of impact,” he says.
During the press conference, the holder of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical normative, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM indicated adequate conditions for take-off, and as the aircraft progressed to the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were layers of low-level cloudiness.
Selected routes:
It is likely that because of the cloud conditions the crew sought an area of lower height and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Localization of impact.
The impact coordinates and the last aircraft record on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a reduced zone:
The information available so far suggests that the impact has occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The aircraft's remain dispersion model assumes that the helicopter has collided against the ground under structural integrity conditions.
Traces of fire or explosion were not detected:
In the disaster location there is still no trace in the aircraft remains of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the fieldwork, aircraft parts were found at a height of 9 thousand 200 feet above the average sea level, the ground had a slope that had been going from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he may have disarticulated along his journey.
The information provides evidence that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful research in a larger area than the encircled location, around the accident, dispersed parts of the aircraft were not found, which supports the presumption that the impact occurred under structural integrity conditions.
MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
