He explained that the objective of this investigation and that of knowing the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and identifying risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the objective is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of familial heredity of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that Saturdays will apply anthropometric measurements (weight, height, circumference of size), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (seeks to identify people associated with childhood obesity) will be applied to all participants.
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years there was an increase in the 77 percent in obesity and in the case of 47 per cent girls in the case of overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed," said the IMSS specialist.
He said the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others by its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have a 65 percent Indo-American heredity, a 30 percent European and a five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy that is consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the integral evaluation of children, which makes it possible to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
Ila even says that the presence of dark colored folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering metabolic and even pre-diabete alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, physicians give it in writing to the parents, to whom each of the measures and changes in the lifestyle they must make to prevent disease is explained.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transport instead of going on foot on short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the greatest consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat pâté with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrant
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the reports that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand blackcurrant each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the asphalt paver is adequate, the blackcurrant could be reduced or even eliminated.
During his conference A technological opinion on blackcurrants, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the yield, and therefore, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the majority of the streets of Ciudad de México were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the small stones that forms the layer, he signaled, is bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles pass through it by generating forces, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, stubbornly stumble.
On the asphalt layer, he says, a last layer is put called rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip in the street.
Being the part of the block that receives and distributes the forces, the rolling layer also requires that the latter have an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be neat.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and consequently causes blackcurrant.
In the trial of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one that spoils is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
