Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is one subject that cannot be dealt with from short-term considerations or emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is healthy that an electoral meeting is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place that nuclear power holds in them.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of the demand for electricity by 2050, unless we deprive a huge part of the world’s population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to compensate for the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity permanently, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight against climate change, a subject that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is neither the case of Belgium, which is subjecting its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor of Switzerland, which just intends to build only state-of-the-art power plants.
Conversely, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, continue their projects with determination.
The United States, on the other hand, decided after Fukushima to add a unit to their park by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, focused on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality thwarts discourse.
Berlin's choice will result in higher electricity prices, an energy dependence exacerbated by the increased use of imported gas, particularly from Russia, a jump in CO2 emissions driven by the construction of gas and coal-fired power plants.
In a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already felt.
The case of Denmark is to be meditated.
European wind champion, from which he draws 30% of his electricity, he is also one of the biggest users of coal and gas because of the intermittency of the wind; according to which, his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the fine statements on the reindustrialisation of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show an opposition in principle to this energy, the polls show it.
Recall that the energy policy of our country has made it possible to build an industrial sector of 125 000 direct jobs and 410 000 jobs induced.
Strongly exporting, it leads a galaxy of specialized SMEs in international markets and makes them very creative of non-relocable jobs.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear power, it would be sacrificing many of these SMEs by reducing as a skin of sorrow the 6 billion euros annual of French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to work sixty years when the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of production of miracle electricity, nor is there any diabolical.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions is a testament to the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
We have in France a safety authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing plants as well as on the Flamanville construction site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident is the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented scale that have caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it had done for the previous two.
The result of this approach and cooperation between the French and German security authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that enables it to withstand such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians wishing to build a power plant, the stoppage of its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to the competitors of Areva and EDF by leaving them the way clear to seize the leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to leave the emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers to dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "countries of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Libération of May 23) proclaiming in passing that France "does not need foreign talent, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
It is that there is a fairly broad consensus on this subject between left and right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country comprising nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "can not accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left as on the right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden for the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be given to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande confines himself to banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be paying for electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book summarizing the most recent knowledge of immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and hurting employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants risk replacing national workers, particularly the low-skilled, putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly in occupations in sectors with employment shortages.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national wage earners, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not track jobs.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country that is experiencing a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make it possible to arrive immigrants have a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real wages in the long term.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average up to 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labour Organization estimates that, in Germany, an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (less expenditure revenue) of 150000 euros to public budgets on average over his entire life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of the mandate, to go for the points of growth missing "with the teeth".
The teeth in question, by serving to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, remains to think of European democracy
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember it, which, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be sufficient, for democracy to triumph definitively from its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even be made "instrument of oppression" as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public mind, values, an organization, a separation and a control of powers, an education, the Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are living in is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and first of all a crisis in politics and democracy.
