From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is expanding
Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
Long-suspected, the links between the terrorist group al-Qaida in the Islamic Maghreb (AQIM) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram are confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers has now "acquired certainty".
“The way the two organizations operate and the intelligence services’ reports show that there is cooperation,” he said.
Paris seems to be doing a similar analysis.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have uncovered bridges.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by relatives of Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day at the same time as several of their captors during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerien investigators had to find several phone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of the calls made directs several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues are of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigerien who has stayed at length in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram and the other to a man who says he is close to AQIM and the sect.
“This is a step forward, but we must probably wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between AQIM and Boko Haram.”
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect has external financial and intellectual support and that it is becoming more and more active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "supports" have been increasingly evident in the evolution and discourse of Boko Haram or in its modus operating procedures, which now involve the use of suicide bombers or explosive devices that are increasingly complex and of the same bill as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore put pressure on Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of enlightened people who are not very worthy of interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist iman Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which in hausasa means "western education is a sin" - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Muslim Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is a rapid success.
It is politicizing itself and demands strict respect for Sharia law while its activists engage in the fight against the unholy central government.
The latter are aimed first at churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active, increasing attacks on police stations.
Abuja's reaction is, as usual, without nuances.
The army invades the city, there are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, is killed in prison.
From then on, the sect will become radicalized and leave its northern strongholds.
Last Christmas, she claimed responsibility for an attack that killed 80 people in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, it is still in Abuja that Boko Haram attacks the secure headquarters of the police during a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would sail from Mauritania to Somalia to Nigeria is now of concern to all security specialists.
While AQIM has invested Mali and Niger, which al-Shebab’s Somalis are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram appears to be a new threat in the heart of the continent.
Last week, in a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was ready "to share all the intelligence".
The world according to Republican presidential candidates
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete for simplism and ignorance.
Can a crisis-weakened America manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe it.
In recent days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the others have multiplied thunderous statements and shortcuts in foreign policy, traditionally a Republican strong point.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, the slogans - often unsupported - are emerging.
Mitt Romney, the best placed in the race to nominate the "Grand Old Party", threatened to drag the Chinese in front of the WTO and question them "for manipulating their currency", a promising theme in an America exasperated by the migration of entire swathes of his industry to Asia.
Too bad if it has to involve the outbreak of a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama’s former ambassador to China and the only candidate to have a sophisticated foreign policy vision, almost strangled himself in the face of an attitude that “flatters” emotions.
He called for a muscular but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama’s current position).
But Huntsman, who stagnates in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
Like Reagan
Romney has also promised military strikes on Iran if the sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
"If I'm elected, I'll stop Iran," he boasted.
"If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb."
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to meet his obligations to this partner.
The entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second best-placed candidate, displays an embarrassing lack of knowledge of the files.
Recently, he called for countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing is "trying to develop a nuclear capability" - apparently unaware that China has held the military atom since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants strikes on Iran, says he is ready to engage the U.S. military in Mexico against drug cartels.
The use of torture against suspected terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
We are far from the 2008 Republican candidate, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
The opponents of the current president respond that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to put water in his wine when it came to counterterrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naïve dialogue with Iran, on the overly precipitous departure of the "boys" from Iraq, on his procrastination in Libya, thus sticking him with a label of weakness.
But the attack is not so easy.
The population considers the national security record of Obama, who eliminated bin Laden, rather positive.
From Iraq, she is wary of military interventions that lead to bogged down.
And, arguing that we need to rebuild America economically to resurrect his leadership, Obama strikes more accurately.
Nord Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, connecting Western Europe directly to Russia by moving to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with radiance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new pipeline that connects directly, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands Mark Rutte have together turned the wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first tube of 1,224 km connecting the region of St. Petersburg to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same course.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site has the air of victory.
The project was strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will indeed make it possible to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it is becoming more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to close access to the West European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland, in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a breach between Europeans in the East and the West.
Russia has, in just five years, made its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, heavily gas-consuming, and whose deposits are in decline triumph.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon, inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete sheathed steel to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
“A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
Measures also had to be stepped up to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, that nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off Sweden, but project officials gave up while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company permanently established off their coast.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds to experience a leak every 100 000 years.
The monitoring of the condition of the gas pipeline is provided by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, at a time wide in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it delivers precise information on the possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repair.
The flow of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which keeps 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) were joined.
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty years renewable, all the capacity to transport gas.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided at 30% by the shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to go into their expenses, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that is coming, before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
He has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its rectangular black cover, elastic, off-white leaves, as if aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin (skin of mole) which designates a varnish cotton used to cover benches for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought back to life an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
The success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million coins sold.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3 000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Difficult to establish a portrait-robot of the buyer, because the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, his consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its early stages, has almost 100 today and has had two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to small downtown shops and has imposed her identity.
“We followed the air of the time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified his products: bags, agenda, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a range of supports.
A success that made envious: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled is opening today.
Despite a proactive public policy put in place in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, director general of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled. "
"The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher. "
"There is still a lot to be done. "
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many barriers before they have access to employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students of higher education, only 10 000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for disabled people, compared to 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that particularly complicate the return to employment, and that "constitute the knot of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
Still the unsaid, the mentalities that evolve, certainly, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "over-representation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual deficients".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, which date back to 2008, report a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, managing director of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, increasing 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc. "
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
